(5 comments)

I think this looks good overall. I've a few outstanding questions besides the nitpick:

1. Should v1 API return 413 or 404 looks good?

2. Can we make changes to the glance docs / (wiki, if applicable) that adds this new status?

3. I've not tested this locally however, if any other reviewer did I would be happy to pair with them to see if we've covered functional test cases around this. (Sorry, I'm finding it difficult to find more cycles for reviewing this thoroughly.)

Patch Set 5: Code-Review-1

(1 comment)

Thanks for working on this worth one, Eddie.

I'm worried on direct location stuff in v2 api [0], deactivated image bits could be accessed via its location directly from store, I think probably we need to update status of image location in db as well ('active' => 'deactivated', e.g.) - it also could help the location status be consistent with the image, and filter them out when query, like [1].

BTW, +1 to update doc, like in-tree image status transformation diagram at [2]

[0] https://github.com/openstack/glance/blob/master/glance/api/v2/images.py#L659

[1] https://github.com/openstack/glance/blob/master/glance/db/sqlalchemy/api.py#L176

[2] https://github.com/openstack/glance/blob/master/doc/source/images_src/image_status_transition.dot (and https://github.com/openstack/glance/blob/master/doc/source/images/image_status_transition.png )

Patch Set 6: Code-Review-1

If image is cached then user is able to download after deactivating the image.

1. Create the image
2. Download the image (image will be cached)
3. Deactivate the image
4. Download the image, it downloads the image successfully.

IMO, here also it should give HTTPForbidden as image is deactivated.

Applicable for v1 and v2 api.
